{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538150"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16151"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16151"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.12,0.14,0.5,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4685"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43614"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of high fever, vomiting, and diarrhoea. She had been well in the preceding days, apart from having some mild menstrual cramps. She is menstruating and uses tampons, which she reports changing infrequently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has recently returned two days prior from a short-trip to Bali, Indonesia where she indulged in eating at the local food markets and went drinking with fellow backpackers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. She has a diffuse, erythematous, blanching rash over her trunk and extremities. Her conjunctivae are injected, and her oral mucosa appears hyperaemic. Abdominal examination reveals generalised tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pyogenes","Clostridium perfringens","Hepatitis A","Staphylococcus aureus","Neisseria meningitidis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features classic for toxic shock syndrome (TSS), including high fever, hypotension, diffuse rash, vomiting, diarrhoea, and mucosal hyperaemia. The association with tampon use during menstruation is particularly suggestive of staphylococcal TSS. TSS occurs when vaginal colonisation with toxin-producing strains of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E leads to systemic illness. While rare (affecting 1-3 women per 100,000), the condition is life-threatening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnostic criteria for TSS include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever \u226538.9\u00b0C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypotension\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWidespread macular erythroderma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDesquamation of skin within two weeks after onset\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDysfunction of three or more organ systems (gastrointestinal, muscular, hepatic, renal, haematological, neurological or mucosal)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of TSS, particularly in menstruating women using tampons. The condition is caused by toxin-producing strains, specifically toxic shock syndrome toxin-1 (TSST-1) and enterotoxins. These toxins act as superantigens, triggering massive cytokine release and subsequent systemic inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a similar toxic shock-like syndrome due to exotoxins. However, it typically occurs with soft tissue infection or surgical wounds rather than tampon use, and often presents with severe localised pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E is a viral infection transmitted via the faecal-oral route which can cause vomiting, diarrhoea and fevers. While travel to endemic areas like Bali and consuming food from local markets are risk factors, hepatitis A typically presents with jaundice, right upper quadrant pain, and elevated liver enzymes. It does not cause the diffuse rash, hypotension, or mucosal changes seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause meningococcaemia with shock and rash, but the rash is typically petechial or purpuric rather than diffusely erythematous. Meningeal signs would also be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with gas gangrene and food poisoning. While it can cause toxin-mediated illness, it does not typically present with the characteristic features of TSS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recurrence rate of menstrual TSS is approximately 30-40% in women who continue to use tampons. Treatment involves immediate removal of any tampon, fluid resuscitation, and broad-spectrum antibiotics including anti-staphylococcal coverage. Antibiotics with anti-toxin properties are preferred (e.g., clindamycin), and intravenous immunoglobulin should also be considered for patients who do not respond to fluid resuscitation. Patients should be advised to avoid tampon use in the future, or if tampons are used, to change them frequently and use the lowest absorbency necessary.  Reminders on the phone may also be utilised to prevent forgetting to change the tampons.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Toxic shock syndrome is most commonly caused by toxin-producing Staphylococcus aureus, particularly in menstruating women using tampons.","Clinical features of toxic shock syndrome include fever, diffuse rash, hypotension, and multi-organ involvement.","Early recognition and removal of any potential source (e.g., tampon) is crucial in managing toxic shock syndrome."],"references":["Billon A, Gustin MP, Tristan A, B\u00e9net T, Berthiller J, Gustave CA, et al. Association of characteristics of tampon use with menstrual toxic shock syndrome in France. EClinicalMedicine. 2020 Apr;21:100308.","Atchade E, De Tymowski C, Grall N, Tanaka S, Montravers P. Toxic Shock Syndrome: A Literature Review. Antibiotics (Basel). 2024 Jan 18;13(1):96. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10812596/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84473"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16151"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84473"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-06T13:04:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T13:04:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},